                    {
                      "type": "frame",
                      "id": "cF1Zh",
                      "name": "WritingCanvas",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "height": "fill_container",
                      "fill": "$surface-canvas",
                      "layout": "vertical",
                      "gap": 16,
                      "padding": [
                        32,
                        40
                      ],
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "CsCpa",
                          "name": "canvasText",
                          "fill": "$text-primary",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "The global race to regulate artificial intelligence has entered a decisive phase, with the world's three largest economic blocs charting fundamentally incompatible paths — a divergence that will shape the technology's trajectory for decades.\n\nDistinct frameworks have crystallized in the past eighteen months. The European Union's AI Act, adopted in March 2024, establishes the world's first comprehensive risk-based classification system. High-risk applications — from biometric identification in critical infrastructure management — face mandatory conformity assessments, while general-purpose AI models must meet transparency obligations that scale with their systemic influence.\n\nThe United States has chosen a lighter touch. Executive Order 14110, signed in October 2023, relies on safety testing mandates and voluntary commitments from frontier AI developers rather than the EU's prescriptive categorization. The approach reflects a preference for industry self-governance, tempered by federal oversight only at the frontier of capability.\n\nChina's regulatory architecture, meanwhile, has evolved through a series of targeted regulations — on algorithmic recommendations (2023), deep synthesis (2023), and generative AI services (2023). Rather than a single omnibus law, Beijing has constructed a layered system that prioritizes content governance and social stability alongside innovation promotion.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.8,
                          "fontFamily": "$font-mono",
                          "fontSize": 13,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
